+# Coefficient-Corrected Triad-Phase Orbit Ledger Is The Best Current Intrinsic Object
+
+Status: `INFERRED` intrinsic-object verdict with `VERIFIED` exact transfer
+identity
+
+On the current record, the strongest surviving intrinsic phase object is the
+coefficient-corrected triad-phase orbit ledger built from
+`z_tau(a) = C_tau a_p a_q overline(a_k) / (|C_tau| |a_p| |a_q| |a_k|)` and
+the associated orbit phases `Theta_tau(a) = arg z_tau(a)`.
+Equivalently, the object may be recorded as the multiset or measure
+`Mu_S(a)` of those phases over the active exact triad orbits.
+
+This is the exact phase combination entering the normalized transfer identity
+`Re(C_tau a_p a_q overline(a_k)) = |C_tau| |a_p| |a_q| |a_k| cos Theta_tau`.
+So it records transfer-facing phase data without prelabeling which triads are
+supposed to be good or bad.
+
+Because the raw formula names only exact interaction data and survives
+conjugate completion, triad relabeling, helical-basis rephasing, gauge
+choices, and uniform amplitude normalization, the branch should treat the
+orbit-level triad-phase ledger as the primary exact phase object rather than a
+desired-channel score.
+
+Filed from:
